II to an extraordinary reconstruction of airpower use in the Gulf War, based on recently declassified documents. In this now-classic work of the theory and practice of airpower and its political effects, Robert A. Pape helps military strategists and policy makers judge the purpose of various air strategies, and helps general readers understand the policy debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAir powervCase studies. 0aBombing, AerialvCase studies. 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aAirpower Studies.  aAxis Powers.  aConflicts.  aGermany 1942-1945.  aHistory.  aIraq 1991.  aJapan 1944-1945.  aKorea 1950-1953.  aMilitary Aviation History.  aMilitary Coercion.  aMilitary History.  aMilitary Issues.  aMilitary Strategy History.  aNational and International Security.  aPersian Gulf War.  aUS bombing strategy.  aUnited States Air Force.  aUnited States Airforce School of Advanced Airpower Studies.  aUnited States.  aVietnam 1965-1972.  aVietnam War.  aWars.  aWorld War II.  aaerial bombing.  aair power and coercion in war.  aamerican war history .  abombing strategy.  acase studies in aerial bombing.  acase studies on air power.  acases of coercive air power.  acoding cases of strategic bombing.  aefficacy of coercive bombing.  aefficacy of strategic bombing.  amilitary history.  amilitary strategy.  apolitical science strategy.  asecurity affairs.  astrategic air offensives.  astrategic bombing.  astrategies of military coercion.  asuccess and failures of military coercion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147151340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isb